{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RVzHgAEDaMXRyVGNzMc1ZJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1**: The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about verifying that data from all three sources is assembled and passed together to the summary step. This is a data aggregation/wiring behavior — it could fail if the orchestration code doesn't collect from one source or doesn't pass collected data correctly.\n- Is this Unit or Integration? The failure would be: one source's data not being included. This could be tested by wiring the three data-fetching modules together with the orchestration module. With stubs for the HTTP clients, you can test whether the aggregation logic properly calls all three and collects results.\n\n\n- REAL-INFRA: The data sources are a metrics endpoint, an issue tracker API, and a deployment log. Stubs would suffice here since we're really testing whether the orchestrator calls all three and assembles their results, not whether the actual HTTP calls work.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Stubs work fine for this — the failure is in the aggregation logic, not in real infrastructure behavior.\n- LLM-DEP: Not applicable at this stage.\n- Minimum level: Integration — you need the data fetchers, orchestrator, and summary input wired together. A unit test might miss if the orchestration logic spans multiple modules.\n\nFor Behavior 2, I'm thinking about what happens when a data source fails. The code should produce a report with a `data unavailable` note instead of aborting entirely. This could be tested at the unit level if it's a single function's error handling, but since the orchestrator needs to handle failure from one of the three sources and continue, Integration is the right level to catch whether that handoff actually works.\n\nFor Behavior 3, I'm now looking at whether the LLM-generated summary accurately captures the key values from the input data. This one has an LLM dependency, which changes the testing approach.\n\nFor Behavior 4, I need to verify the entire pipeline works end-to-end: pulling from multiple data sources, generating the summary through the LLM, and delivering the final report via email to the recipient. This requires real infrastructure for both the LLM calls and email delivery, making it an agentic-level test that spans multiple steps.\n\nFor Behavior 5, I'm thinking through the error handling scenario where the email service fails. The system should persist the generated report to disk and reschedule delivery for the next run. This involves real filesystem operations and the scheduler mechanism, though I'm still clarifying whether we need an actual unreachable email server to fully test this scenario. achable\" part could be simulated with a stubbed client that raises connection errors.\n- Does it need real filesystem? Writing to a local file could be tested with a real temp directory.\n- The \"next scheduled run\" aspect requires testing the scheduler or persistence mechanism.\n- LLM-DEP: The report was already generated; this is about save/retry behavior. No LLM needed.\n- REAL-INFRA: File writing + scheduler state. The file save could use temp dir (Integration), but the \"retried on next scheduled run\" part could require either mocking the scheduler or running a real subprocess/scheduled job.\n\nThe key question is whether \"retried on next scheduled run\" means calling the main function again in a test with a persisted flag on disk (Integration level), or if it requires the actual scheduled task to execute as a subprocess (System level). If the retry logic just checks for a saved state file and re-processes it, I can test that with a temp directory and two function calls. But if the failure only manifests when the script is actually invoked by the OS scheduler, that pushes it into System territory.\n\nI'm leaning System because the failure mode involves the script being re-invoked, which is typically a subprocess boundary.\n\nNow for Behavior 3: \"Accurately represents the key values\" — this is about the quality of the summary itself. That's harder to test automatically without an LLM evaluation or manual inspection.\n\nThe retry logic hinges on whether the scheduler state is just a file flag or an actual OS-level scheduled task, so I'll classify this as System since real script re-invocation is likely involved.\n\nFor Behavior 4, I'm seeing multiple real steps: actual HTTP calls to APIs, real LLM invocation for the summary, and real email delivery. That's a Workflow-level test because it involves orchestrating multiple agentic components.\n\nNow I'm assigning probability distributions across the test levels. Behavior 1 is mostly Integration with some chance it's just a Unit test if it's a single function. Behavior 2 is similar — the error handler could be tested in isolation, but more likely needs Integration. Behavior 3 is trickier since summary quality is subjective, so it leans Agentic. Behavior 4 is clearly Workflow given the multiple real external interactions.\n\nFor Behavior 5, which involves infrastructure and configuration, System testing dominates the probability distribution, though Integration and Workflow also have meaningful chances depending on how the test is structured.\n\nNow I'm checking plan consistency: Behavior 1's test description should require wiring multiple modules together, which confirms Integration level. Behavior 2 needs an orchestrator plus a stubbed failing source plus report generation.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10000,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10000},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"316ae36d-a5e3-40c7-995e-bd52d9bffe9b","uuid":"22af7eea-8bf2-4c53-9372-5d2b872999c0"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RVzHgAEDaMXRyVGNzMc1ZJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01StqJ5NMg9bTxoTDJ5LZQAE","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is that the orchestration layer silently drops one source's data before passing it to the summary step — this is a module-boundary bug between the three fetchers and the aggregator. A single-function Unit test can't catch this unless all three fetch calls and the aggregation are inside one function, which is unlikely. REAL-INFRA: Real HTTP is not needed; stubs returning canned payloads are sufficient because the failure is in the wiring/aggregation logic, not in HTTP transport behavior. LLM-DEP: No AI/ML involved at this stage. REJECTION-GATE for System: The behavior asks about what is *passed* to the summary step, not about real network calls — an in-process stub for each API suffices.","test_description":"Wire three stub data-source clients (metrics, issue tracker, deployment log) into the real orchestrator function. Each stub returns a distinct canned payload. Call the orchestrator and intercept or inspect the argument passed to the summary-generation function. Assert that all three payloads are present in that argument, with no source omitted or overwritten.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.11,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode — script aborts instead of continuing — only appears when the orchestrator receives an exception from a fetcher module and must decide whether to propagate or swallow it and continue. That decision crosses a module boundary (fetcher → orchestrator → report assembler), so Unit is too low. REAL-INFRA: A stub that raises a connection/timeout exception is sufficient; we do not need a real unavailable server to trigger the code path. LLM-DEP: No AI/ML needed — we're testing error handling, not summary quality. REJECTION-GATE for System: The behavior says 'unavailable', which triggers in-process exception handling; no real network failure is required to exercise the branch.","test_description":"Wire the real orchestrator with two stub sources that return valid canned data and one stub that raises a connection error. Run the orchestrator end-to-end (up to, but not including, the summary-generation step, which can be stubbed). Assert: (a) execution completes without raising, (b) the assembled report data structure contains valid entries for the two healthy sources, and (c) the failing source's section contains a 'data unavailable' marker.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.11,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: 'Accurately represents' is a quality claim about generated text — it depends on what the real language model produces given the input. A stub always returns the same canned string and will always pass, hiding any drift in model behavior, prompt regression, or context truncation. Running this test 100 times with a real model could produce varying results precisely because accuracy is the thing under test. MOCK-HIDE: Any deterministic stub would make this test vacuous. REAL-INFRA: The test needs a real LLM/generation API call. REJECTION-GATE for Workflow: Only one generative step is described here — the summary step alone — so multi-step chaining is not required.","test_description":"Call the real summary-generation function (backed by the live LLM API) with a fixed, realistic input containing specific numeric values (e.g., deployment count, open-issue count, error rate). Assert that the returned narrative string mentions those specific key values and does not contradict them (e.g., does not describe a failing metric as healthy). Run with at least 3 independent samples and require the assertions to pass on all of them to account for non-determinism.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.73,"Workflow":0.12}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The behavior explicitly spans: (1) three real data-source API calls, (2) a real LLM summary-generation call, and (3) real SMTP/email-API delivery — each is a distinct agentic or I/O step. REAL-INFRA: 'Reaches the recipient's inbox' requires a real (or sandboxed) email delivery channel; an in-process email stub can't verify deliverability. LLM-DEP: The pipeline includes the summary-generation step, whose correctness is model-dependent. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing any step collapses the test to a lower level and hides cross-step failures (e.g., character encoding from the LLM breaking the email body, or a large payload from one API being truncated before the summary step). REJECTION-GATE for Agentic (single-step): More than one agentic/real-I/O step is required — data APIs + LLM + email — so Workflow is warranted.","test_description":"Run the full scheduled script end-to-end against a staging environment: real (sandbox) metrics endpoint, real (sandbox) issue tracker, real deployment log fixture, live LLM API, and a test mailbox via a real SMTP relay or email testing service (e.g., Mailpit, Mailtrap). After script completion, poll the test inbox and assert: (a) exactly one email arrived, (b) the subject and recipient match configuration, (c) the body contains sections for all three data sources, and (d) the body contains a non-empty narrative paragraph.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.16,"Workflow":0.72}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: Two distinct OS-level behaviors are required. First, the report must be persisted to the real filesystem (a temp-dir works, but we need actual file I/O, not an in-memory mock, to verify the file exists after a crash or process exit). Second, 'retried on the next scheduled run' requires re-invoking the script as a fresh process to confirm that the persisted state (pending report file or flag) is discovered and the retry is attempted — this is a subprocess boundary that in-process tests cannot cover. MOCK-HIDE: An in-process mock of the file system would miss bugs in path construction, permissions, or encoding. Mocking 'next run' as a second function call in the same process would miss failures in the startup/discovery logic. LLM-DEP: No new generation is needed for the retry path. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: The 'next scheduled run' clause explicitly requires a process restart; an in-process call-twice pattern cannot catch failures in the script's initialization and pending-report discovery logic.","test_description":"In a test with a real temp directory: (1) run the script as a subprocess with a stubbed email service that returns a connection-refused error; assert exit code is 0 and a report file exists in the configured fallback directory. (2) Run the script again as a second subprocess (simulating the next scheduled run) with the same stubbed email service now returning success; assert the previously-saved file is consumed (deleted or moved) and the email stub received the report payload. Also assert that a third run with no pending file makes no extra email calls.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.23,"System":0.58,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.1}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10000,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10000},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"316ae36d-a5e3-40c7-995e-bd52d9bffe9b","uuid":"7a551ca6-2662-44d2-99cc-9a835121a36b"}
